{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #375 [status: falsifiable; formalized: yes]. Is it true that for any $n,k\\geq 1$, if $n+1,\\ldots,n+k$ are all composite then there are distinct primes $p_1,\\ldots,p_k$ such that $p_i\\mid n+i$ for $1\\leq i\\leq k$? Current best: Note this is trivial when $k\\leq 2$. Grimm proved that this is true if $k\\ll \\log n/\\log\\log n$. Erd\\H{o}s and Selfridge improved this to $k\\leq (1+o(1))\\log n$. Ramachandra, Shorey, and Tijdeman \\cite{RST75} have improved this to\\[k\\ll\\left(\\frac{\\log n}{\\log\\log n}\\right)^3.\\]This is problem B32 in Guy's collection \\cite{Gu04}. Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_51f38920b6c6e358","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos375.erdos_375 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos375.erdos_375.","id":"vf_f49c46c940fbd237","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"every composite run up to limit has an SDR (honest null)","claimed_status":"","classification":"importable_attempt","id":"vat_52680301dbdb4d3b","kind":"computation","lifecycle":"historical","location":"git_history_only","mathematical_scope":"bounded","method_channel":"","method_families":["bipartite_matching","hall_violation_search","exhaustive_bounded_search"],"named_obstructions":["unbounded_composite_runs"],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":["Replace the bounded search through 12000000 with a uniform argument or a counterexample."],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_52680301dbdb4d3b","trust":"signed"}],"activity_types":["attempt","computation"],"attempt_count":1,"banked_attempt_count":1,"commits":[{"commit":"121807e20b06eb8148f594dfe13e440181252b0f","repository":"erdos_frontier","source_root":"sha256:210e6e1b2ca15973f38386a512f1f8fa66bbae72bb1b9acb1daf2e669ab279c7"},{"commit":"7815f5fd21f13df75f77c0ea0fd9637b095b1fb3","repository":"vela_history","source